('chemsoft', 4, 'Problem Statements', '<br><br><ul><li><a href="./events/chemsoft_problem1.pdf" target="_blank">Problem Statement 1</a><br><br></li><li><a href="./events/chemsoft_problem2.pdf" target="_blank">Problem Statement 2</a><br><br></li>\r\n<li><a href="./events/chemsoft_problem3.pdf" target="_blank">Problem Statement 3</a><br><br></li><!--\r\n<li><a href="./events/chemsoft_problem4.pdf" target="_blank">Problem Statement 4</a><br><br></li>--></ul>', 'y'),
('scrapheap', 1, 'Introduction', '<h4 align="center">ROAD TO RESURRECTION</h4><br/><br/><br/>\r\n<p align="justify"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/scrapheap.jpg" width="50%" align="left" alt="scrapheap"></img>"And I to my motorcycle Parked like the soul of the junkyard Restored, a bicycle fleshed with power, and tore off Up Highway 106 continually Drunk on the wind in my mouth wringing the handlebar for speed Wild to be wreckage forever"<br/><br/>\r\nIt is said that every product eventually becomes a waste. Can a waste become a useful product? Scrapheap is an event that explores this idea to a fruitful conclusion.Thisevent is an ideal mesh of education and entertainment.This event expects educational demonstrations of basic technological principles with a raucous, fast-paced, head-to-head contest among the participants. <br/><br/>\r\nRacing against the clock, teams scrap together working models to carry out a particular mission, using whatever minimum resources that they are provided. And in the end, it doesn''t matter so much who wins -- there is no cash reward, just a trophy and bragging rights. It''s all about making something remarkable with limited resources.It''s hard to make science much cooler than that! \r\n</p>\r\n', 'y'),
('scrapheap', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>\r\n<b>Round 1</b><br><br/>\r\n\r\n<b>General Aptitude Test</b><br/><br>\r\n\r\nThis is an elimination round in which all the registered teams will be subjected to a test that will evaluate their general level thinking and the ability to comprehend on the spot.<br/><br/><br/>\r\n\r\n<b>Round 2</b><br/><br/>\r\n<b>Prelims Solution and Description to the given problem</b><br/><br>\r\nThis is also an elimination round where the shortlisted teams from the first round will be given a set of problems for which they have to give a detailed descriptive solution on paper. It''s purely a written round and judges you only on your innovativeness and creativity.<br/><br/><br/>\r\n\r\n<b>Round 3</b><br/><br/>\r\n<b>Final Showdown</b><br/><br/>\r\n\r\nIn this round the shortlisted teams from the second round will be given some scrap materials and they will have to make a working model according to the problem statement. It is not necessary to use all the scrap provided.<br/><br/>\r\nFor example, you are given scrap materials like cardboard, aluminium sheet, threads, marbles, nails and pins and you have to make a weighing balance that automatically distributes weight (marbles) to its pans on both sides as you add any number of marbles.<br/><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n', 'y'),
('science_expo', 1, 'Introduction', 'coming soon', 'y'),
('code_masters', 1, 'Introduction', '<br /><br /><p align="justify">All programming lovers are invited for an event that is designed to bring   \r\ntogether the sharpest minds and test the best of the participants in programming.   \r\nIt has been rightly said that computer is the dumbest machine. So do you think \r\nyou can add some intelligence to it? Jigyasa presents the programming   \r\ncontest where you can match your logic and programming skills with the \r\nstudents from schools across the country. <br /><br />\r\n \r\n<i>"The world is changing very fast. Big will not beat small anymore. It will   \r\nbe the fast beating the slow."</i> - Rupert Murdoch <br /><br /></p>\r\n ', 'y'),
('olympiad', 1, 'Introduction', 'coming soon', 'y'),
('acquizitions', 1, 'Introduction', '<br><br><h4 align="center">Ritz, Blitz and Quiz</h4><br><br>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n\r\n<img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:10px" src="http://avishkar.in/events/acquizitions..gif" width="50%" align="left" alt="image is loading..."></img>\r\n\r\n\r\nThink you know much about brands, mergers, jargons and all that corporate jazz? Think when it comes to quizzing you rely on your intellectual grasp and instinctive guts much like the bigwigs of the Biz-world you envisage? Then why not come for acQUIZitions and be sure of it! <br><br>\r\nacQUIZitions - the first ever business quiz of MNNIT promises you everything that biz and quiz together stand for -zest for knowledge, intuitive risks, competitive acumen and needless to mention - profits. So if you have interest, intellect and a partner (one man armies can also be entertained); you are cordially invited to seize the day.\r\n<br><br></p>\r\n', 'y'),
('essay_writing', 1, 'Introduction', '<br><br><p align="justify"\r\n>Man is a Social animal. For the healthy existence of a person in a society it is necessary that the \r\nperson is able to communicate his/her thoughts in an organized manner. Communication has its own \r\nmeans, one of them is speaking and another is writing. Both differ in their own ways and a person \r\nuses the one which he feels is more convenient. WRITING is one such means of communicating and \r\nESSAY WRITING is an excellent means where a person can share his ideas, organize his thoughts, add \r\nhis creativity and project solutions to various issues. Essay writing can be fun as it gives the liberty to \r\nthe writer to express his views, write poems or jingles or add some comedy. So all those people who \r\nlike expressing themselves and sharing their ideas with the world, Essay writing is the way to do that. <br><br>\r\n<i>I was uncomfortable writing fiction. My love was the personal essay, rather than \r\nthe novel - Alain de Botton. </i><br></p>\r\n', 'y'),
('lab_tours', 1, 'Introduction', '<br><br><p align="justify"><i>"Darwin investigated the numerous facts obtained by naturalists in living nature and analysed \r\nthem through the prism of practical experience." </i>\r\nTrofim Lysenko <br><br>\r\nBooks and notebooks all the time is''nt a whole lot of fun!! And neither are they stimulating \r\nenough for students who aspire to go that extra mile. Well this is an occasion for all those school \r\nstudents who wish more than just bookish knowledge. Who crave to learn through experience and think \r\nout of the box.<br><br>\r\nSo come and experience the richness and exuberance of the campus life at MNNIT-Allahabad. \r\nThe tour involves various visits to state-of-the-art laboratories(including the machines lab,the \r\nmechanical engineering lab,the electronics and communication lab,etc) and the Computer Centre. <br><br>\r\nThe purpose is to give the school-going students a brief overview regarding modern day science \r\nand engineering and be introduced to the latest developments in the field of technology. It aims to \r\ninvoke curiosity among the budding brains and inspire them to <b>INNOVATE</b> and <b>CREATE</b>.....<br><br>\r\n<center><b>Come and witness the phenomenon that is MNNIT-Allahabad!!</b></center>', 'y'),
('counter_strike', 2, 'Event Format', '<br/><br/>\r\n<h4 align="center">Kreedomania 2011 will use Counter-Strike v1.6 (non-steam) in 5 versus 5\r\nin-game players.\r\nThis Coordinating Committee reserves the right to modify the rules and\r\nregulations from time to time without notice. It is encouraged to review\r\nthese rules and regulations from time to time in order to be apprised of\r\nany changes.\r\n<br/> </h4><br/><br/><br/>\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Single  Map Match:</em></strong><br/><br/>\r\n  A  &ldquo;single map match&rdquo; is played on a single map and opposes two teams of\r\n  5  players each. Each team will play as terrorist and counter-terrorists\r\n  Alternatively  in two half-times of 15 in-game rounds. The team winning 16\r\n  In-game  rounds in total will be the winner and the match will be finished\r\n  There  only without playing any further rounds.\r\n  In  case of a tie, that is when both teams have won 15 rounds each at the\r\n  End of  two half-times, the winner will be decided by a <em>Tie-Breaker Match</em>.<br/> </p><br/><br/>\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Best-Of-Three  Match:</em></strong><br/><br/>\r\n  A  best-of-three match is played as three Single Map Match on three\r\n  different  maps and opposes two teams of 5 players each. The team\r\n  winning  two Single Map Match will be the winner. There won&rsquo;t be a 3rd\r\n  Single  Map Match if a team wins the first two Single Map Match of its bestof-\r\n  three  match.<br/><br/>\r\n  Only  the last three matches of the tournament, that is the final and the two\r\n  semi-finals,  will be played as a Best-of-three match. Rest all the matches\r\n  will  be Single Map Match.<br/> </p><br/><br/>\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Tie-Breaker  Match:</em></strong><br/><br/>\r\n  A  tie-breaker match is analogous to a Single Map Match with two halftimes\r\n  of 3  in-game rounds. First team to win 4 in-game round wins.<br/> </p><br/><br/>\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Round  Time:</em></strong><br/><br/>\r\n  1  minute 45 seconds.<br/> </p><br/><br/>\r\n<p align="center"><a href="events/Counterstirke site content.docx">Download: <u><font color="#FF0000">Counter Strike Brochure</font></u></a></p>', 'y'),
('counter_strike', 3, 'Game Settings', '<br/><br/>\r\n<h4 align="center">Game  Version:<br/> \r\nThe  competition uses the Half-life - Counterstrike v1.6 mod (non-steam)<br>\r\n  PC  game.<br/>\r\n</h4><br/><br/><br/>\r\n\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Tournament  Server Settings:</em></strong><br>\r\n  -  mp_autokick 0 - mp_autocrosshair 0<br>\r\n  -  mp_autoteambalance 0 - mp_buytime 0.25<br>\r\n  -  mp_consistency 1 - mp_c4timer 35<br>\r\n  - mp_fadetoblack  1 - mp_flashlight 1<br>\r\n  -  mp_forcechasecam 2 - mp_forcecamera 2<br>\r\n  -  mp_footsteps 1 - mp_freezetime 15<br>\r\n  -  mp_friendlyfire 1 - mp_hostagepenalty 0<br>\r\n  -  mp_limitteams 10 - mp_logecho 1<br>\r\n  -  mp_logdetail 3 - mp_logfile 1<br>\r\n  -  mp_logmessages 1 - mp_maxrounds 0<br>\r\n  -  mp_playerid 1 - mp_roundtime 1.75<br>\r\n  -  mp_timelimit 0 - mp_tkpunish 0<br>\r\n  -  sv_aim 0 - sv_airaccelerate 10<br>\r\n  -  sv_airmove 1 - sv_allowdownload 0<br>\r\n  -  sv_allowupload 0 - sv_alltalk 0<br>\r\n  -  sv_cheats 0 - sv_clienttrace 1<br>\r\n  -  sv_clipmode 0 - sv_friction 4<br>\r\n  -  sv_gravity 800 - sv_lan_rate 25000<br>\r\n  -  sv_maxrate 25000 - sv_maxspeed 320<br>\r\n  -  sv_maxunlag 0.5 - sv_maxupdaterate 101<br>\r\n  -  sv_minupdaterate 101 - sv_minrate 25000<br>\r\n  -  sv_proxies 1 - sv_send_logos 1<br>\r\n  -  sv_send_resources 1 - sv_stepsize 18<br>\r\n  -  sv_stopspeed 75 - sv_unlag 1<br>\r\n  -  sv_voiceenable 1 - sv_unlagsamples 1<br>\r\n  -  sv_unlagpush 0 - sys_ticrate 10000<br>\r\n  -  allow_spectators 1 - decalfrequency 60<br>\r\n  -  edgefriction 2 - host_framerate 0<br>\r\n  - log  on - pausable 0<br>\r\n  . <br>\r\n  ...... <br><br>\r\n  <strong><em>Allowed  Setting Values for Client:</em></strong><br>\r\n  -  cl_updaterate 101 - cl_cmdrate 101<br>\r\n  - rate  25000 - m_filter 1/0<br>\r\n  -  hud_fastswitch 1/0 - zoom_sensitivity_ratio<br>\r\n  -  fps_max 101 - cl_dynamiccrosshair 1/0<br>\r\n  -  gamma 1/3 - brightness 1/3<br>\r\n  -  cl_minmodels 1/0 - cl_shadows 1/0<br>\r\n  . <br>\r\n  ...... <br>\r\n  <strong><em>Following  Client Settings that must not be Changed</em></strong><br>\r\n  <strong><em>(Must use  the default values):</em></strong><br>\r\n  - cl_weather  1 - mp_corpse_stay<br>\r\n  -  mp_decals - max_shells<br>\r\n  -  max_smokepuffs - fastsprites<br>\r\n  -  ex_interp 0.01 - cl_lw<br>\r\n  - Video  Settings :- 32 Bit<br></p><br><br>\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Game  Settings In Overtime:</em></strong><br>\r\n  The  following game settings will be used specifically for overtime halftimes:<br>\r\n  - mp_startmoney 16000<br>\r\n  - mp_maxrounds 3<br></p><br><br>\r\n<p align="justify"><strong><em>Official  Maps:</em></strong><br>\r\n  - de_dust2<br>\r\n  - de_inferno<br>\r\n  - de_train<br>\r\n  - de_nuke<br></p><br><br>\r\n', 'y'),
('counter_strike', 5, 'Contacts', '<p align="center"><b><a href="mailto:counterstrike.avishkar2k11@gmail.com">counterstrike.avishkar2k11@gmail.com</a> </center></b></p><br><br>\r\n<table><tr height="40px">\r\n  <td width="400px">Naveen Kumar</td>\r\n<td width="400px">+91-7860062200  </td><td width="400px"> naveen.669786@gmail.com </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="40px">\r\n  <td width="400px">Amit Kumar Meena</td>\r\n<td width="400px">+91-  8909654393</td>\r\n<td width="400px"> amit.in.mnnit@gmail.com  </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="40px">\r\n  <td width="400px">\r\nGaurav Srivastva</td>\r\n<td width="400px">+91-  9795634359</td><td width="400px"> gkv22008@gmail.com </td></tr>\r\n\r\n</table>\r\n<br><br>', 'y'),
('quince', 1, 'Introduction', '<br/><br/>\r\n<h4 align="center">Quince is a rescue robot equipped with four sets of tracked wheels, some of which can move up and down to allow the robot to negotiate obstacles. It can carry pay load as well for  resue of  survivors trapped under the influence of strong tsunami.</h4><br><br><br>\r\n\r\n<p align="justify">There are two villages Red and Green inbetween there is  a Lake.Due to a stong tsunami the belogings of villagers flew away with the  wind into the lake.Now the villagers are asking for help to rescue their  belongings which are precious to them.<br><br>\r\nYou are the person with your Electronic Robotic Machine only who is  capable of completing the task.Now grab your boots to get into the aqua to  prove yourself and stand their hope.Be responsible to rescue the respective  belongings to the respective villagers.Be careful as a lake is not an easy  place to be and be quick so that you dont let their belonging get damaged.<br><br>\r\n\r\nProve Yourself to be the fastest of all other resuers  that will make you The  Bot  Resuer.&#13;<br><br></p><br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p align="center"><a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheet/viewform?formkey=dGtmYnBtbnRBSU42M0dYOG85VkdmaHc6MQ" target="_blank"><b>Click to Register </b></a></p><br><br>\r\n', 'y'),
('quince', 2, 'Event Format ', '<br><br>\r\n<b>Gameplay:</b><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Pre-Game Setup</b><br/><br/>\r\nThe participants will get 5 minutes of setup time for  calibration and testing prior to \r\nthe competition according to a schedule that will be  made available at the start of \r\nthe event. In the setup time, participants cannot drop  their bot in water.<br><br><br>\r\n<b>Game Procedure</b><br/><br/>\r\nThe competition will be divided into 2 rounds.<br>\r\n<br>\r\nRound 1 - Elimination Round<br><br>\r\nIn this round, the rescue bot will have to collect the  ball from the arena and deposit\r\nthem in the collection pit in minimum possible time.<br><br>\r\nRound 2 - Knockouts<br><br>\r\nTop teams from  round 1 which deposit the balls in the minimum time will qualify for\r\nround 2.And the  Final Competetion will be played among the selected teams.<br><br><br>\r\n<p align="center">Downloads: <a href="events/quince.pdf" target="_blank"><u><font color="#FF0000">Quince the RESCUE BOT Brochure</u></font></a> || <a href="events/quince.skp"><u><font color="#FF0000">3-D Sketch UP</a></font></u></p>', 'y'),
('quince', 3, 'Specification', '<br><br><b>Arena:</b><br><br>\r\n<a href="events/quince1.jpg" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/quince1.jpg" width="40%" align="left" alt="fig1"></img></a>\r\n<a href="events/quince2.jpg" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/quince1.jpg" width="40%" align="right" alt="fig2"></img></a>\r\n<br><br>\r\nThe arena consists of the following zones -  <br><br>\r\nRed Village zone (indicated by red colour square in figure )<br><br>\r\nGreen Village zone (indicated by green colour square in  figure )<br><br>\r\nLake zone (indicated by water in figure )<br><br>\r\n\r\nFigure 1 and figure 2 shows the 3D and top view of arena  respectively. <br><br>\r\n\r\nThe surface of both the villages consists of a  timber(plywood). <br><br>\r\nThe lake will be formed of fresh water and bricks would  be used as the obstacle.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Note: &#13;</b><br><br>\r\nFigure has been coloured just to distingush the various zones in the arena.<br><br>\r\nAll dimensions are approximate to  within a 5% margin of error.&#13;<br><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Specifications:</b><br><br>\r\n<b>Ball Specifications</b><br><br>\r\nThe balls would be red and green in colour.The balls  would be standard TT ball.<br><br>\r\n<b>Robot Specifications</b><br><br>\r\nThe robot must be mannually controlled and made by the  contestent itself.<br><br>\r\nUse of lego kits is not allowed.<br><br>\r\nMaximum operating voltage must not exceed 24V DC.<br><br>\r\nEvery innovative designs will be entertained. The  dimension of the bot must be decided  considering the arena itself.<br><br>\r\nHowever the bot must fit into a cube of 300  mm x 300 mm x 350 mm (lxbxh) at all times<br><br>\r\nThe power supply may or may not be provided onarena.<br><br>\r\nIt can communicate only with the operator using  wired/wireless data transfer.<br><br>\r\nA bot is allowed to collect only one ball at a time  before depositing.<br><br><br><br>\r\n\r\n', 'y'),
('quince', 4, 'Rules', '<br><br><b>Game Rules:</b><br><br>\r\nWhile starting, the rescue bot will be placed in the  starting zone marked in figure .<br><br>\r\nThe timer will start, as soon as the field cordinater  gives the start signal.<br><br>\r\nThe rescue bot should collect and deposit the balls in  the collection zone.<br><br>\r\nThe bot will be awarded points only after the ball has  touched the collection zone.<br><br>\r\nIf a ball drops in between it will be taken back and  launched again. <br><br>\r\nIf there is any circuit failure few minutes can be  granted.<br><br>\r\nThe timer will be stopped during this procedure. <br><br>\r\nThe teams can take a restart during that time.<br><br><br>\r\nThe organisers reserve the right to change any or all of the above rules as they deem\r\n fit. Change in rules, if any, will be highlighted on the website and notified to the \r\nregistered participants.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Team Specification</b><br><br>\r\nA team may consist of a maximum of 4 members. Students from different \r\neducational institutes can form a team.<br><br>\r\n<b>Eligibity</b><br><br>\r\nAll students with a valid identity card of their respective educational institutes are eligible to participate.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>NOTE: ONLY FIRST YEAR STUDENTS ARE ALLOWED TO PARTICIPATE.</b><br><br>\r\n<b>Certificate Policy</b><br><br>\r\nCertificate of excellence will be awarded to the top 3 winners. Certificate of participation will be awarded to the teams that deposit a minimum of 1 balls in the elimination round.INSERT INTO `tabs` (`id`, `tab_no`, `name`, `description`, `display`) VALUES
('robocop_the_saviour', 3, 'Gameplay', '<br><br>\r\n<b>GAMEPLAY:</b><br><br>\r\n<ol type="1">\r\n  <li>Each  team will start their operation by placing their robot in the starting points.  After switching on the robot, no team member will be allowed to touch or  communicate with the robot in any manner during the whole operation. However,  one member from the team is allowed to handle the wires of the power supply in  case of external power supply. <br><br></li>\r\n  <li>Each  team is given the time of maximum <strong>10  minutes</strong>. The timer will start as the robot start its operation.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>The  robot will start traversing the radiation zone to search for the blocks.<br><br> </li>\r\n  <li>If  the robot encounters the first S Block, then it has to give a signal of <strong>green light</strong> and deposit the S block in  the safe zone. The first S Block can be deposited in any side of the safe zone.<br><br>\r\nPoints for the deposition of  first S Block:<br><br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>50  points will be awarded for the correct light signal (green light in the case of  S Block)<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>100  points will be awarded for the successful deposition of the first S Block in  safe zone completely.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>50  points will be awarded if the block is deposited partially inside the safe  zone. Partially means the some part of the block is in the safe zone and  remaining is in radiation zone.<br><br></li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n  <li>If  the robot encounters the second S Block, then again it has to give a signal of <strong>green light</strong> and deposit the S block in  the safe zone. Now, there are two different cases of deposition of second S  Block. <br><br>\r\n <ul>\r\n  <li>50  points will be awarded for the correct light signal (green light in the case of  second S Block).<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>Case  1: 200 points will be awarded if the second S block is placed in the side of  the safe zone which is vacant.<br><br>\r\n100 points will be awarded for  the partial deposition in Case 1. <br><br></li>\r\n  <li>Case  2: 100 points will be awarded if the second S block is placed in the side of  the safe zone in which the first S block was deposited.<br><br>\r\n\r\n50 points will be awarded for the  partial deposition in Case 2.<br><br></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n  <li>If  the robot encounters the first T Block, then it has to give a signal of <strong>red light</strong> and deposit the T block in  the prison zone. The first T Block can be deposited in any side of the prison  zone.<br><br>\r\nPoints for the deposition of  first T Block:<br><br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>50  points will be awarded for the correct light signal (red light in the case of T  Block)<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>100  points will be awarded for the successful deposition of the first T Block in  prison zone completely.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>50  points will be awarded if the block is deposited partially inside the prison  zone. Partially means the some part of the T block is in the prison zone and  remaining is in the radiation zone.<br><br></li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n  <li>If  the robot encounters the second T Block, then again it has to give a signal of <strong>red light</strong> and deposit the T block in  the prison zone. Now, there are two different cases of deposition of second T  Block. <br><br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>50  points will be awarded for the correct light signal (red light in the case of  second T Block).<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>Case  1: 200 points will be awarded if the second T block is placed in the side of  the prison zone which is vacant. <br><br>\r\n100 points will be awarded for  the partial deposition in Case 1.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>Case  2: 100 points will be awarded if the second T block is placed in the side of  the prison zone in which the first T block was deposited.<br><br>\r\n50 points will be awarded for the  partial deposition in Case 2.<br><br></li>\r\n</ul></li>\r\n\r\n  <li>There  is <strong>no restriction on the sequence of the  deposition of the four blocks</strong>. It means that the robot can just deposit the  block as it encounters them.<br><br></li><li>200  points will be awarded as bonus if the robot, after depositing the four blocks,  finally lands itself in the safe zone and stops. The robot should stop itself  automatically in the safe zone, not manually like by switching off the power  supply and any other means. <br><br></li>\r\n  <li>No bonus points will  be awarded if the robot stops itself somewhere else other than the safe zone or  it does not stop even.<br><br> </li>\r\n\r\n  <li>The operation will be  called complete if all the four blocks are deposited either completely or  partially in their respective zones.<br><br> </li>\r\n  <li>If the robot completes  its operation successfully in T seconds, then it will be awarded a bonus  of (600 - T)/2 points. Please note  that this bonus will be awarded only when the operation is complete (as  explained in previous point).<br><br></li>\r\n\r\n  <li>During the operation,  if any block gets displaced from its original location and lies somewhere else  in the radiation zone, it will be picked up and put back to any other random grid  point in the radiation zone.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>Restarts: <br><br>\r\n <ul> <li>Each  team can have a maximum of<strong> three  restarts</strong>. During a restart, timer will be stopped and the robot will have  to be restarted by putting it back in the grid starting point in the radiation  zone. In a restart, the timer will not be set back to zero.<br><br> </li>\r\n  <li>During  restart, all the deposited blocks will be retained at their positions and the  un-deposited blocks (in the radiation zone) will be reshuffled.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>During  restart, a contestant cannot feed information about the grid to the bot.  However, contestants are allowed to: Adjust sensors (Gain, Position etc.), make  repairs. However, a contestant may not alter a robot in a manner that alters  its weight (e.g. removal of a bulky sensor array or switching to lighter batteries  to get better speed).<br><br></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n  <li>Penalties:<br><br>\r\n  <ul><li>A  penalty of 20 points will be awarded every time when the robot goes out of the  radiation zone without carrying any block.<br><br> </li>\r\n  <li>A  penalty of 20 points will be awarded if the robot gives a wrong light signal  when it encounters any block. No penalties are incurred if the robot does not  give any light signal.<br><br> </li>\r\n  <li>No  penalties will be awarded if the robot places a block in the wrong zone. But in  this case, the operation will not be called complete and the time bonus of (600 - T)/2 will not be awarded.<br><br></li>\r\n</ul></li><ol>\r\n<br><br>', 'y'),
('robocop_the_saviour', 2, 'Specification', '<br><br><b>ARENA:</b><br><br>\r\n<a href="events/robocop_arena1.png" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/robocop_arena1.png" width="40%" align="left" alt="arena1"></img></a>\r\n<a href="events/robocop_arena2.png" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;\r\nborder-top-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px;;border-top-width:100px;" src="events/robocop_arena2.png" width="40%" align="right" alt="arena2"></img></a>\r\n<a href="events/robocop_arena3.png" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/robocop_arena3.png" width="40%" align="center" alt="arena3"></img> </a>\r\n\r\n<ol type="1"><li>Arena comprises of a black background and the grid which is identified by the white strips.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The arena will consist of an<b> 8 x 8 squares grid </b>of white lines on a black surface. The lines will be equally spaced. Each cell of the grid will be a square with inner dimensions <b> 220 mm x 220 mm</b>. The thickness of each white line is 30 mm.<br><br></li> \r\n<li><b>Please note that the actual arena will be totally black and white in colour. The coloured arena has been shown to have a better understanding of the problem.</b><br><br></li>\r\n<li>The whole arena is divided into four zones :<br/><br/>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Starting Zone: </b>The robot can start the operation at any one of the four starting points. These points are located at the corners of the radiation zone and marked by a square. The size of the square is <b>220 mm x 220 mm.</b> The autonomous robot should completely lie inside the starting zone at the start of its operation.<br><br/></li> \r\n\r\n<li><b>Radiation zone in red colour:</b> This zone consists of <b>5 x 5 squares grid.</b> The four blocks will be placed only inside the <b>inner 4 x 4 intersection points</b> in the radiation zone.  The four blocks (two scientists and two terrorists) are initially placed in this zone randomly. The autonomous robot has to search for the blocks in this zone only.<br><br></li>\r\n\r\n<li><b>Safe zone in Green colour:</b> This is the zone in which the autonomous robot has to deposit the two scientist blocks. This zone is made on the two sides of the arena. The robot can place the scientist block anywhere in the safe zone, not necessarily on the intersection points of the grid, but it should be totally inside the safe zone. <br><br></li>\r\n\r\n<li><b>Prison Zone in Blue colour:</b> This is the zone in which the autonomous robot has to deposit the two terrorists blocks. This zone is also made on the two sides of the arena. The robot can place the terrorist block anywhere in the prison zone, not necessarily on the intersection points of the grid, but it should be totally inside the prison zone. <br></li></ul></li></ol><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>BLOCKS:</b><br><br>\r\n<a href="events/robocop_block1.png" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/robocop_block1.png" width="40%" align="left" alt="block1"></img></a>\r\n<a href="events/robocop_block2.png" target="_blank"><img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:60px" src="events/robocop_block2.png" width="40%" align="right" alt="block2"></img></a>\r\n<br><br>\r\n<ol type="1"><li>There will be total four blocks with the dimension of 80 mm x 80 mm x 80 mm.<br><br> </li>\r\n<li>There are two types of blocks : <br><br>\r\n<ul><li>S Block: This block denotes the scientist and all the six faces of this block will be white in colour.  <br><br></li>\r\n<li>T Block: This block denotes the terrorist. The top and the bottom faces will be white in colour. The four side faces will be half white and half black. The upper half (40 mm x 80 mm) will be white and the lower half (40mm x 80 mm) will be black.\r\n<br><br></li></ul></li>\r\n<li>All the four blocks will be equal and light in weight. The exact weight will be uploaded soon.<br></li></ul></li></ol><br><br>\r\n\r\n\r\n<b>SPECIFICATIOS OF THE ROBOT:</b><br><br>\r\n<ol type="1"><li>Each team must have only one autonomous robot.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The top view of the robot must fit in the square of dimension<b> 200 mm x 200 mm.</b><br><br></li>\r\n<li>There is no constraint on the height of the robot.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The robot must be able to stand on its own at the starting point before the start of the operation and during the whole operation. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>During the run, the autonomous robot can expand itself provided it does not damage the arena in anyway but should not split into two parts. However, it is not allowed to leave anything behind or make any marks while traversing the grid. <b>Any robot found damaging the arena will be immediately disqualified. </b>The final decision is at the discretion of the organisers.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The methods of collection and delivery of the blocks are at the discretion of the team. However, the teams damaging the blocks will be disqualified. <b>The teams are allowed to use ready-made micro-controller boards/ready-made sensor kits. However they are not allowed to use lego kits or any similar assemblies.</b><br><br></li></ol>\r\n<b>POWER SUPPLY:</b><br><br>\r\n<ol type="1"><li>Teams are allowed to use internal onboard power supply as well as external power supply.<br><br></li> \r\n<li>Each team shall bring its own power supply (internal as well as external) for its robot. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>The teams will be provided with the 230 V, 50 Hz power socket.<br><br></li>\r\n<li><b>The potential difference between any two points on any of the bots must not exceed 24 V DC.</b><br><br></li></ol><br><br>\r\n', 'y'),
('debugging', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br><br>There will be 2 rounds.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<strong>Preliminary Round:</strong><br><br>\r\nDuration : 2 Hrs<br><br><ol type="1">\r\n\r\n<li>Paper will contain multiple choice questions to check your C and C++ knowledge.</li><br>\r\n<li> A separate section for testing your ability to use tools like gdb, objdump, ltrace, ptrace etc.</li><br>\r\n<li>Some questions (in C and C++) containing bugs, which you need to find and fix, will be there.</li><br>\r\n<li>Some coding questions may be there to check your programming.</li><br>\r\n<li>Separate cut-off and marking criterion for teams of first year students.</li><br>\r\n<li>Based on performance in this round teams will be selected for final round.</li></ol><br>\r\n<br>\r\n<strong>Final Round:</strong><br><br>\r\nDuration: 3 Hrs<br><br>\r\nThis round will contain:<br><br> <ol typr="1">\r\n<li>Questions for finding bugs and explaining behavior of programs.</li><br>\r\n<li>Tasks for crashing , reverse-engineering and exploiting programs.</li><br>\r\n<li>Finding most-beloved Segmentation-Faults and their reason.</li><br></ol>\r\n<br><br>\r\nDon''t be surprised if you feel yourself in middle of die-hard 4.0 during this round.\r\n<br><br>\r\n', 'y'),
('debugging', 4, 'FAQS', '<br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 1.</td><td><br>I am first year, I have not studied C and C++ in detail. is there any consideration for us?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br></td><td>There will be separate cut off for first and second year in prelims and some relaxation will be given in final round.\r\n </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 2.</td><td>Will there be any negative marking?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:</td><td>There will be negative marking and the details will be given during the examination\r\n</td></tr>\r\n</table><br/><br/>\r\n', 'y'),
('robocop_the_saviour', 4, 'Rules', '<br><br>\r\n<b>GENERAL RULES:</b><br><br>\r\n<ol type="1">\r\n  <li>Each team can have a maximum of 5 members.<br><br></li>\r\n  <li>The robot is not allowed to leave anything behind while traversing the grid. It should not make any marks on the floor of the arena. Any robot found damaging the arena will be immediately disqualified. <br><br></li>\r\n  <li>The organizers may stop any robot at any time if they feel that it is performing, or is about to perform, any action that is dangerous or hazardous to people or equipment. No robot is allowed to use any flammable, combustible, explosive or potentially dangerous processes.<br><br> </li>\r\n  <li>The time measured by the organizers will be final and will be used for scoring the teams. Time measured by any contestant by any other means is not acceptable for scoring. <br><br></li></ol><br>\r\n    In case of any disputes/discrepancies, the organizers'' decision will be final and binding. The organizers reserve the rights to change any or all of the above rules as they deem fit. Change in rules, if any will be highlighted on the website.<br><br>\r\n  <b>Teams are requested to regularly check the site for any new updates or modifications in the problem statement. </b><br><br><br><br>\r\n<b>JUDGING CRITERIA:</b><br><br>\r\n<ol type="1">\r\n  <li>The total score of the team will be calculated as <br>\r\n  <center>Total score = Points earned + Bonuses - Penalties faced</center><br></li>\r\n  <li>In case of tie, the team with the minimum penalty will be preferred. The final decision remains at the hand of the judges.   <br><br></li>\r\n  <li>A special recognition will be given to the most creative and innovative design. This decision will be taken by the judges. <br><br> </li>\r\n</ol><br><br><br><br>\r\n\r\n', 'y'),
('inception', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>This is an  individual event, open for all the branches of first year.<br>\r\nThe event will  consist of following rounds<br><br>\r\n<strong>Round  1</strong>:-<br>\r\n  This round will be written  round containing questions related to Logical Reasoning,<br>\r\n  Quantitative Analysis, Data  Interpretation, Puzzles and similar Aptitude related Problems.<br><br>\r\n<strong>Round  2</strong>:-<br>\r\n  This round will comprise of  technical problems (you need not panic if you dont have a<br>\r\n  technical background i.e.  you are not familiar with any programming languages, we will be instructing you  properly and this will be a test to judge your learning ability), real life  problems and puzzles.<br><br>\r\n<strong>Round  3</strong>:-<br>\r\nThis  round will comprise of interviews<br><br>', 'y'),
('inception', 4, 'FAQS', '<br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 1.</td><td><br>Being a first year student, I do not know much in Computer Science and its Applications. Will I be able to perform well in this event?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br></td><td>Yes.<br>\r\nEven if you don''t know anything in computer science, you can perform well. All you\r\nneed to have is just good Logical Ability and Reasoning Skills.\r\n </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 2.<br><br></td><td >If this event does not require any knowledge in Computer Science, then, why is this event under Cyberquest?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br><br></td><td>The reason for this event being under Cyberquest is that some problems those will be given in main rounds of the event will be related to Computer Science.But we will be checking your logical abilities and not your programming skills. We dont expect technical stuff from you.\r\n</td></tr>\r\n</table><br/><br/>\r\n', 'y'),
('insomnia', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>The event has 2 stages as follows:<br><br>\r\n\r\n <b>Preliminary round</b><br><br>\r\n  	<ol type="1">    \r\n<li>This will be a written round consisting of objective questions on c, c++, data structures, algorithms.</li><br>\r\n<li>Other then this there will be few algorithmic questions for which you will be required to present an optimal solution and may be have to write a pseudocode.</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>Based on performance in this round teams will be selected for final round.</li><br></ol>\r\n\r\n<b>Final round</b><br><br>\r\n     <ol type="1"> <li>Final round will be an algorithm extensive programming round. The solutions will be accepted by an online judge.</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>It will be of 6 hrs starting from 7 pm during Avishkar. Dates will be confirmed soon.</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>6-8 problems would be there, of varying difficulties according to their marks.</li><br>\r\n\r\n<li>The way of taking input/output will be explained at time of event.</li>\r\n<br>\r\n<li> No act of indiscipline will be tolerated.</li>\r\n<br>\r\n<li>gcc, g++, java 1.4 jdk compilers will be provided to the participants.</li>\r\n<br>\r\n<li>Only one computer will be provided to each team.</li><br></ol>\r\n\r\n\r\n<br>', 'y'),
('fpga', 1, 'Introduction', '<br><br>\r\n<h4 align="center">"Gateway to the future of electronics".\r\n</h4><br><br><br>\r\n<p align="justify">	<img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/fpga.jpg" width="50%" align="left"  alt="fpga"></img>\r\nFPGA design contest, introduced in Avishkar 2011, is back with a bang!! The event of extensive\r\nprogramming and digital logic designing in a technically challenging environment to test your intellect\r\nand ingenuity at developing digital circuits with multitudes of constraints.<br><br>\r\n\r\nField Programmable Gate Arrays (FPGAs) are integrated circuits designed to be configured by the\r\ncustomer or designer after manufacturing - hence the name "field programmable". FPGA Design Contest\r\nrequires one to write the code for the given problem statement in either VHDL or Verilog and optimize\r\nit, then dump the code on the FPGA Kit to physically realize the design that was coded.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br><br><br> </p><br><br>\r\n', 'y'),
('connections', 1, 'Introduction', '<br><br>\r\n<h4 align="center">Connections: revitalize the electricity within\r\n\r\n</h4><br><br><br>\r\n<p align="justify">\r\n<img style=" border-bottom-style:solid;border-right-style:solid;border-left-style:solid; border-color:transparent; border-width:8px; border-bottom-width:20px" src="events/connections.jpg" width="50%" align="left"  alt="connections"></img>Our brain seems not to consume much power, and "whilst a 5-watt light bulb won''t light \r\nthe inside of a refrigerator, a focused 5-watt laser would easily burn right through \r\nthe metal door of that same refrigerator." So if you have the same focus, \r\nconnections is the place for you. Come and storm your brains to the escapade of CONNECTIONS, \r\nan event solely for trical geeks.\r\n\r\n\r\n<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br> <br><br><br><br> </p>\r\n', 'y'),
('mobile_mania', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>It consists of two rounds.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<strong>ROUND 1.</strong><br><br>\r\nYou will be given some problems. You have to implement ANY ONE of them. These problems will be extremely easy. It is just for us to know that you have started implementing things.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<strong>ROUND 2.</strong><br><br>\r\nThis round is the final round. You have to submit a mobile application based on the list of ideas we will provide or you can develop on your own idea. You can send and consult us for your ideas and its implementation.<br><br>\r\n\r\n', 'y'),
('mobile_mania', 3, 'Problems', '<br><br>\r\n<b>ROUND 1</b>:&nbsp;<a href="http://avishkar.in/events/mobilemania.pdf"><b>MobileManiaRound1.pdf</b></a><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>ROUND 2</b>:&nbsp;<a href="http://avishkar.in/events/mobilemania2.pdf"><b>MobileManiaRound2.pdf</b></a><br>', 'y'),
('mobile_mania', 5, 'FAQS', '<br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 1.</td><td> I don''t know anything about Mobile apllications. How can I participate?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br></td><td>If you know Java or C++ or Python or any other OOP language, then surely you can do it.\r\n </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 2.</td><td >Where should I start?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br><br><br><br></td><td>For Android platform: There has been an excellent documentation available online at<a href=" http://developer.android.com" target="_blank"> <b><u>http://developer.android.com.</u></b></a> For Java: all you need to know is, which Java version your mobile supports, and get its corresponding SDK. Also, you can get help from <a href=" http://developer.sun.com" target="_blank"> <b><u>http://developer.sun.com.</u></b></a> You can look on Forums of mobile companies (Google Android, Nokia, Samsung) to get more info. You can also contact us on our email ids for further help.\r\n</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 3.</td><td> How will I convey my idea for Round2?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br><br><br></td><td>You have to submit your ideas (along with the code, ofcourse) in a README file consisting of idea, assumptions, how to run the app, configuration details, or any other point you think is worth mentioning about your app. If you are able to attend the fest, you can contact any of the co-ordinators and show them your application for round2.\r\n\r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n</table><br/><br/>\r\n', 'y'),
('software_design', 2, 'Event Format', '<strong>Round 1:</strong><br><br>\r\n<b>First years :</b>The round will have three problems out of which , you have to solve any 2. The problem will be simple software development problems of varying difficulty. One problem has to be solved in java.<br><br>\r\n<b>Second/Third years :</b> The round will have four problems out of which , you have to solve any two. The problems will be of varying difficulty , will carry different marks.<br><br>\r\nSecond years and third years will be evaluated separately.<br>\r\nBesides the working code of the problem , you have to submit the design of your software as well.<br>\r\nThere will be a presentation wherein you have to present your solution and explain the\r\ndesign and working. You have to submit your code as well.<br><br>\r\nThe solution will be judged on the basis of the following grounds.<br><br><ol type="1">\r\n<li>Whether the solution meets the minimal requirements or not.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The additional features one has implemented. Make your solution better and more innovative.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The design of the solution.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>Your knowledge about the problem domain.<br><br></li>\r\n<li>The presentation of your solution during the ppt.<br><br></li></ol>\r\n<b>Round 2:</b><br><br>\r\nThis will be a coding+design round. You will be given 15 problems which will test your\r\nknowledge of java and other fields like computer science , use of advanced IDEs, GUI programming etc.There will be some problems which have to be solved strictly in java. The problems will be of varying difficulty and hence will carry different marks.<br>This will be an open book round. You can bring any and as many books as you wish. Electronic media like pen drives are not allowed.<br><br>\r\nThe top 6 or 7 teams will qualify for the round 3. There will be separate papers for first years and second/third years. Second years and third years will be evaluated separately.<br><br>\r\n<b>Round 3:</b><br><br>\r\nThis is the final round.<br><br>\r\nThis will be an interview round. You have to come in formals strictly. There will be 2 or 3 interviews which will test your knowledge of java and other core computer concepts like Data structures, Database etc. All the years will be evaluated and interviewed differently.<br><br><br>', 'y'),
('softathalon', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>\r\nEvent will be containing total four rounds  as follows:<br><br>\r\n<ol type="1">\r\n<li>First round will be a written round which will check your aptitude skills and technical skills. It will be an objective round  with few one line subjective ones.</li><br>\r\n<li>Second round will be a coding round to test your coding ability.</li><br>\r\n<li>Third round will be to check your ability to learn a new language about which you will be entertained later.</li><br>\r\n<li>Fourth round will be final one which will comprise of Comprehensive round  based  interviews.</li><br><br>\r\nMost of the above rounds will be elimination rounds. Further information about this will be conveyed later.</li><br>\r\n', 'y'),
('softathalon', 4, 'FAQS', '<br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 1.</td><td> Are all branches allowed?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:</td><td>Yes, all branches are allowed..\r\n </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 2.</td><td > In coding round are we allowed to bring books for references? </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br></td><td>No hand books, notes , pen drive will be entertained and if anybody found using them , he/she will be debarred from cyberquest immediately.\r\n \r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 3.</td><td >  What topics will be covered in written round so that we can prepare? </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br></td><td>C,C++,data structures, aptitude, algorithms, DBMS, networking, operating system, digital electronics, computer organization, unix for written rounds and area of interest ,Puzzles and Subject Knowledge for interviews .\r\n\r\n \r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n</table><br/><br/>\r\n', 'y'),
('robocop_the_saviour', 5, 'Contacts', '\r\n<br><br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr height="30px"><td width="300px"> Arpit Singh</td><td width="300px">                 +91-9616928392\r\n</td><td width="300px">arpit2009arpit@gmail.com</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="30px"><td width="300px">Deepak Agarwal</td><td width="300px">                +91-8004170575\r\n</td><td width="300px">deepakagarwal1990@gmail.com</td></tr>\r\n</table>         \r\n \r\n', 'y'),
('software_design', 5, 'FAQS', '<br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 1.</td><td>How many rounds of interviews will be there?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:</td><td>This information will be entertained at spot only. There may be more than one round of technical interviews.\r\n\r\n </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 2.</td><td >In Round 2, what is allowed for references? </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br></td><td>Only hand books are allowed. Pen drive or any mass storage devices are not allowed. If anybody found using them anyway, they will be debarred from cyberquest immediately.\r\n\r\n \r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 3.</td><td > Are all branches allowed ?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br></td><td>Yes, all branches are allowed.\r\n \r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 4.</td><td >I don''t know how to design ?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br></td><td>You can contact any of the coordinators for an overview of how to submit/present design.There will be workshop(s) for design,using IDEs like Netbeans and Eclipse,sources etc.\r\n\r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n</table><br/><br/>\r\n', 'n'),
('software_design', 3, 'Problem Statements', '<p align="center">Download: <a href="http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/index.html"><u>JDK and Netbeans Software</u></a></p><br>\r\n<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>1st\r\n year First Round Problems <br><br>\r\n3 problems are to be done. <br><br>\r\n1st\r\n problem is compulsory. <br><br>\r\n2 problems are to be solved out remaining four. <br><br>\r\n1 problem should be solved in java and 1 is open(including java also). <br><br><br></b>\r\n \r\n<ol><li><b>Catch me if you Can! (Compulsory) : </b><br><br>\r\nThe problem statement is simple : <br><br>\r\nCreate a java applet to chase the mouse pointer using any object!(it can be a cat,a fish or any other \r\nobject ).The better the chase ,the more points you fetch!  <br><br></li>\r\n<li><b>Tic-Tac-Toe (100): </b><br><br>\r\nDevelope a GUI based two player 3x3 tic-tac-toe software. Marks will be awarded on design and \r\ngraphics. You can think of some add-ons too to get bonus points. <br><br></li>\r\n<li><b>Calculator (80): </b><br><br>\r\nDevelope a GUI based calculator ( like the one you use in windows ) with as many facilities as you like. <br><br>\r\nMarks will be awarded on design and graphics. <br><br></li>\r\n<li><b>Printscreen (80):  </b><br><br>\r\nIn this problem you guys have to develope a software to capture a screenshot(i.e the currently displayed \r\nimage on the Screen).More points will be awarded if a particular region in the screen can be selected \r\nand converted into an image.The user must be able to save the image in any of the formats like \r\n.gif,.jpg,etc.  <br><br></li>\r\n<li><b>Ctrl-C!! (80)</b>: <br><br>\r\nDevelope a GUI based application to copy a file and also show the progress of the process using  \r\nusing progress bar. <br><br></li></ol>\r\n\r\n<br>\r\n<br /><b>2nd\r\n year/3rd\r\n year First Round Problems <br /><br />\r\n2 problems are to be done. <br /><br />\r\n1 problem should be solved in java and 1 is open(including java also). <br /><br /></b>\r\n<ol><li><b>Open software (100 ): </b><br /><br />\r\nDesign a software of your choice. Anything you could think of. Marks will be awarded on your design, \r\nthe creativity of your idea, the utility if your software, and user friendliness of the software. \r\n  <br /><br /></b></li>\r\n<li><b>ClipBoard Manager : Ctrl-C,Ctrl-V made easier!  (60)</b> <br><br>\r\nNormally,whenever we do Ctrl-C,the copied text is stored in some system buffer.When a new Copy \r\naction is done,the older Buffer Text is lost and is replaced with the newer text.This very thing might be \r\nirritating at times!. <br /><br />\r\nThe idea of this problem is to build a Clipboard manager to store a list of all Ctrl-C''s done by a \r\nuser.Whenever the user wants to paste , he just needs to select the required item from the list and \r\npaste at the required location. <br /><br /></li>\r\n  \r\n   \r\n<li><b>Paint application : Lets paint.. !! (80) </b><br /><br />\r\nA simple paint application having various painting option like drawing shapes , filling colors, writing text. <br /><br />\r\nBasic requirements - line drawing, erasing, free flow drawing using mouse. <br /><br />\r\nMore number of feature will fetch more points.  <br /><br />\r\nBonus Points will be awarded  if your your application would be able to connect to other instances of \r\napplication and to share whatever one is drawing like shared spreadsheet in google.com <br /><br /></li>\r\n \r\n<li><b>Daily diary : (60) </b><br /><br />\r\nDesign a GUI based multiuser daily diary, where user can write, edit and delete notes on various dates \r\nand later on can read/retrieve them as in when required. <br><br> <b>Basic requirements :</b> <br /><br />\r\n<ol><li>Every user has a login name and password to open his account in a diary. New users can also \r\nregister.<br /><br /></li> \r\n<li>A user can retrieve/search , write, edit and remove notes on a particular date of his choice. User \r\nshould be provided with a calendar to choose a date. <br /><br /></li><li>\r\nDiary should be refreshed at the end of each year. <br /><br /></li></ol>\r\n<b>Add ons will be awarded bonus marks : </b><br><br>\r\nAdd-on example are  <br /><br />\r\n<ol><li>You can add alarm functionality so that user can set alarms on particular dates. <br /><br /></li><li>\r\nPrint functionality. <br /><br /></li><li>\r\nText formatting.  <br /><br /></li></ol><br>', 'y'),
('tuxwars', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>The event consists of the following stages:<br><br>\r\n<ol><li><b>Preliminary Round (Only for MNNIT students)</b><br>\r\n	This will be a written round comprising of questions from C, Networking, System Programming , UNIX Shell Programming and System Administration<br><br></li>\r\n\r\n<li><b>Final Round</b><br>\r\n         This round would test your practical skills in all the above mentioned topics as well as some simple hacks. Each team will be provided with one linux machine for this round. The details of the round will be notified during the event.<br /></li></ol>\r\n', 'y'),
('tuxwars', 4, 'FAQS', '<br>\r\n<table>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 1.</td><td>Can a team consist of participants from different colleges?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:</td><td>Yes.\r\n\r\n </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 2.</td><td >I am a first/second year. I don''t know UNIX. Can I participate? </td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br><br></td><td>Yes.<br>\r\nWe will be having special workshops for MNNIT students for tux wars. Also, there will be separate cut-offs for first/second years.\r\n\r\n \r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n<tr height="15"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Q 3.</td><td >My event is clashing with other events. What do I do?</td></tr>\r\n<tr height="8"></tr>\r\n<tr><td width="50px">Ans:<br><br></td><td>You can talk to the co-ordinators for the same. The contacts are available on the contacts page.\r\n\r\n \r\n</td></tr>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</table><br/><br/>\r\n', 'y'),
('horizon', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br>\r\nThe event will be conducted in three stages. <br><br>All three are elimination rounds.<br><br>\r\nThe plan will be evaluated on the basis of its technical, financial and marketing feasibility, innovativeness of the idea, and quality of presentation.<br><br> You need to identify untapped opportunities and prepare plans along the following lines.<br><br>\r\n<ul><li>Macro and micro environment analysis of the industry.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Proposed product / service and market opportunity.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Marketing strategies.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Technical feasibility.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Operating plan.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Financial viability and projections for at least 3 years.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Estimated cost of project and sources of finance.\r\n<br><br></li><li>Hiring Plan\r\n<br><br></li><li>Exit strategy.<br><br></li></ul><br>\r\n\r\n<ol><li><b>Executive Summary Submission:</b><br><br>   The Participants will be required to send their executive summary in less than 4000 words as a soft copy to <b><a href="mailto:horizon.avishkar2k11@gmail.com">horizon.avishkar2k11@gmail.com</a></b><br><br></li>\r\n\r\n<li><b>Preliminary Round (only for MNNIT students):</b><br><br> It shall involve a discussion about your proposed plan in meticulous detail with the organizers. It would be better if you can prepare a PowerPoint presentation till then but it isn''t compulsory.<br><br></li><li>\r\n\r\n<b>Final Presentation Round:</b><br><br> The selected participants will be invited to make a presentation of their plan with the detailed hard copy of the plan. You''ll be required to give a PowerPoint presentation with detailed analysis of different aspects of your business plan in front of the judges.\r\n<br><br><br><br>\r\n<p align="center"><a href="http://avishkar.in/events/horizon_summary.pdf"><b>Download: Sample_Executive_Summary.pdf</b></a></p>', 'y'),
('webster', 2, 'Event Format', '<br><br><strong><u>Round 1: Topic Decision round</u></strong><br><br>\r\n  It is a round in which you are required to  make an Abstract of the website the group wants to work upon.The Abstract will  be a 1-2 pages&nbsp; (at max.) , it will be a  general introduction regarding the way the people want to approach their  respective chosen topic . The abstract will list some salient features that the  website will have and a brief description about how the things gonna work out.<br>\r\n  Some of the necessary points to be included  in the abstract are :\r\n<br><br>\r\n  <ol><li>Platform <br></li>\r\n<li>Languages used<br></li>\r\n<li>Database <br></li></ol>\r\n<br>\r\nWhat happens after that:<br>\r\n  After the people submit their respective  abstracts and they are read , the list of group will be displayed along with  the topic which will be allotted to them on the basis of their respective  abstract submitted .<br>\r\n  <b>Note</b>: This is not an elimination round. <br><br>\r\n  <strong><u>Round 2: Deployment and Elimination Round</u> </strong><br><br />\r\n  The teams will be required to come with  their respective websites and will have to host their website on a webserver .The  teams will be eliminated if they could not meet a particular standard. In case teams want to host their website from their own laptop they are allowed to do so and they will be given a network connection for that. <br><br>\r\n  <strong><u>Round 3: Testing and Presentation Round</u></strong><br><br/>\r\n  This is the final round in which the teams  will have to present their website to the judges of the event. The team will  have to go through rigorous questioning by the panel.<br><br>\r\n', 'y'),
