('pre_defined_hardware', 3, 'Problem Statement 2', '<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>INTRODUCTION </b><br><br>\r\nWith the increase in capability of the processors used in laptops, the need arises for more efficient \r\ncooling methods to be employed to keep the chassis'' temperature within tolerable limits. A common \r\nsolution is to use small fans to circulate air that acts as a heat sink, sucking the heat from the body of \r\nthe laptop.<br><br> <br>\r\n \r\n<b>PROBLEM STATEMENT </b><br><br>\r\nYour task is to design a temperature-based speed controller for a heat sink pump employed in a \r\ncommonly-used laptop or a desktop CPU. The controller takes in temperature data and computes a \r\nsuitable speed depending upon a predefined linear variation between the temperature and speed  for \r\nthe motor driving the pump. <br><br> <br>\r\n \r\n<b>DETAILED DESCRIPTION </b><br><br>\r\nUsing an 8-bit microcontroller, map values in the temperature domain to corresponding values in the \r\nspeed domain. In other words, determine the appropriate fan speed at which to spin the attached fan \r\nbased on the temperature prevailing in the CPU or a laptop. The fan is to be disabled below a \r\nthreshold temperature, decided by the user. Once the temperature detected exceeds the threshold, \r\nthe fan speed is to be increased linearly from zero to maximum fan speed at another set temperature. \r\nIf the temperature continues to increase beyond a certain limit, a warning signal is to be issued using \r\nan LED. <br><br> <br>\r\n \r\n<b>ADD-ONS </b><br><br>\r\nIncorporating the following features will fetch you extra points. <br><br>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Causing an alarm bell to be sounded as warning if the temperature increases the maximum \r\nlimit.<br><br></li> \r\n<li>Instead of using DC power, employ a rectifier to provide the required power from 24 V AC, 50 \r\nHz supply. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Use an LCD to display the following variables: \r\n<ul><li>Current speed of the fan, <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Temperature of the surroundings, <br><br></li>\r\n<li>A warning message in case of temperature exceeding limit.  <br><br></li></ul></li></ul>\r\n  <br>\r\n<b>RULES AND REGULATIONS </b><br><br>\r\n<ul><li>  Use of only 8-bit microcontrollers is allowed. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Use of stepper motors and servo motors is strictly forbidden. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>A maximum of 3 members can form a team, with at least one member from electrical or \r\nelectronics branch. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Decision of the judges will be final and binding. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>ABSTRACT SUBMISSION: An abstract, detailing the approach to the problem and an approximate \r\nsolution would have to be submitted on or before the 15th of September, 2011. <br><br></li></ul> <br>\r\n \r\n<b>JUDGING CRITERIA </b><br><br>\r\n<ul><li>Only teams that solve the basic problem satisfactorily will be considered. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Judging will be done by faculty members of electrical and electronics departments. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Neatness and clarity of the hardware would be considered as well while judging. <br><br></li>\r\n<li>Special credit will be given to more innovative appearance of the hardware. <br><br></li></ul>', 'y'),
